Dialogue: 0,0:47:49.68,0:47:54.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Best one I never saw slavery explained\Nthat way. I think on the history channel
Dialogue: 0,0:47:54.56,0:48:00.80,Default,,0,0,0,,contextualize it in terms of the\Neconomics of the day. Uh the religious
Dialogue: 0,0:48:00.80,0:48:06.64,Default,,0,0,0,,beliefs of the day. Uh the United States\Nhad more money invested in slaves than
Dialogue: 0,0:48:06.64,0:48:12.80,Default,,0,0,0,,in any other industry. It was the\Nbiggest industry of the entire economy.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:12.80,0:48:17.52,Default,,0,0,0,,All different aspects\Nwhich I'd never seen before until it was
Dialogue: 0,0:48:17.52,0:48:22.07,Default,,0,0,0,,contextualized\Nuh from a greater dimension.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:22.07,0:48:27.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Its economic weight, its impact on every\Njust about every aspect of society.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:27.68,0:48:33.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Therefore, relinquishing it was not just\Na religious
Dialogue: 0,0:48:33.11,0:48:40.80,Default,,0,0,0,,uh belief of equality. It had to do with\Npulling the drain on the entire economy,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:40.80,0:48:44.80,Default,,0,0,0,,the entire economy. So now you\Nunderstand it a little bit differently.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:44.80,0:48:49.76,Default,,0,0,0,,You feel a little less judgmental about\Nit. All those bad southerners and all
Dialogue: 0,0:48:49.76,0:48:53.52,Default,,0,0,0,,this.\NAnd when it's recontextualized now, it
Dialogue: 0,0:48:53.52,0:48:57.76,Default,,0,0,0,,takes on a different significance and a\Ndifferent meaning. different meaning.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:57.76,0:49:03.35,Default,,0,0,0,,All right. So, it was the economy of the\Nday.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:03.35,0:49:08.40,Default,,0,0,0,,The ego likes novelty, hates boredom and\Nsameness, and it gets addicted to
Dialogue: 0,0:49:08.40,0:49:12.96,Default,,0,0,0,,thrills. Afras is going to miss out on\Nsomething.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:12.96,0:49:19.92,Default,,0,0,0,,The sound of the motorcycle raising.\NThat's a come on, boys. Get get into the
Dialogue: 0,0:49:19.92,0:49:25.11,Default,,0,0,0,,excitement. Get into the risk. Get into\Nthe danger. Uh yeah, the novelty,
Dialogue: 0,0:49:25.11,0:49:30.24,Default,,0,0,0,,addicted to thrills. People will go to\Nsuch extremes, it's uh mindboggling.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:30.24,0:49:33.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Uh this guy, this Frenchman that has a\Ncompulsion to climb all the tallest
Dialogue: 0,0:49:33.83,0:49:36.96,Default,,0,0,0,,buildings in all the major cities in\NEurope
Dialogue: 0,0:49:36.96,0:49:41.76,Default,,0,0,0,,like a human fly,\Ngoes up the outside of these marble
Dialogue: 0,0:49:41.76,0:49:45.44,Default,,0,0,0,,buildings\Nand they keep arresting him and bringing
Dialogue: 0,0:49:45.44,0:49:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,him down. And in China or someplace,\Nthey put him in jail and beat him with
Dialogue: 0,0:49:50.00,0:49:54.72,Default,,0,0,0,,rods to make him stop doing this thing.\Nand he wouldn't stop. As soon as he's
Dialogue: 0,0:49:54.72,0:50:00.72,Default,,0,0,0,,out, he's back doing it again, you know.\NOh, yeah.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:00.72,0:50:06.31,Default,,0,0,0,,So, he has an addiction to the thrill.\NThe attraction here is to be aggressive.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:06.31,0:50:10.72,Default,,0,0,0,,The fear is passivity.\NHere, you want to gossip and here you're
Dialogue: 0,0:50:10.72,0:50:15.20,Default,,0,0,0,,afraid you're going to be left out of\Nwhat's going on. The addiction to want
Dialogue: 0,0:50:15.20,0:50:20.31,Default,,0,0,0,,to be fashionable instead of being drab.\NAnd of course, it's very necessary to be
Dialogue: 0,0:50:20.31,0:50:26.31,Default,,0,0,0,,right. In fact, being right is more\Nimportant than life itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:26.31,0:50:32.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh yes, people lay down their lives by\Nthe tens of millions.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:32.80,0:50:37.76,Default,,0,0,0,,By the tens of millions, whole\Ngenerations, whole societies, whole
Dialogue: 0,0:50:37.76,0:50:44.07,Default,,0,0,0,,cultures, whole nations,\Nrather than admit they were wrong.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:44.07,0:50:55.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Isn't that something?\N>> The ego's out to kill you.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:55.83,0:51:03.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Better to be dead and right\Nthen wrong and live. Huh? Yeah.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:03.76,0:51:10.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Realize how powerful that is. Whole\Nregimes, whole political parties,
Dialogue: 0,0:51:10.00,0:51:14.24,Default,,0,0,0,,multi-millionaires,\Nall kinds of people stake their entire
Dialogue: 0,0:51:14.24,0:51:21.28,Default,,0,0,0,,life on being right. And they will lie\Nthrough their teeth. They will perure
Dialogue: 0,0:51:21.28,0:51:26.40,Default,,0,0,0,,themselves. They'll put their hand on\Nthe Bible and swear to tell the truth
Dialogue: 0,0:51:26.40,0:51:31.92,Default,,0,0,0,,and lie through their teeth.\NWhen you know how to do kinesiology,
Dialogue: 0,0:51:31.92,0:51:36.96,Default,,0,0,0,,it's always fun to watch the there's\Nalways a major mystery murder murder on
Dialogue: 0,0:51:36.96,0:51:40.55,Default,,0,0,0,,trial.\NThere's always some some kind somebody
Dialogue: 0,0:51:40.55,0:51:44.31,Default,,0,0,0,,is up on some kind of major trial. And\Nof course, within seconds of
Dialogue: 0,0:51:44.31,0:51:47.04,Default,,0,0,0,,kinesiology, you can tell whether\Nthey're guilty or not, you know. So this
Dialogue: 0,0:51:47.04,0:51:52.00,Default,,0,0,0,,guy did it or not. You got it. Now it's\Ngoing to take these 12 people
Dialogue: 0,0:51:52.00,0:51:56.48,Default,,0,0,0,,couple million dollars worth of time,\Nlawyers fees and all. Hey, you already
Dialogue: 0,0:51:56.48,0:52:02.64,Default,,0,0,0,,got it.\NAll right. So being right is very
Dialogue: 0,0:52:02.64,0:52:08.24,Default,,0,0,0,,important to be superior because by\Nbeing right you become superior and you
Dialogue: 0,0:52:08.24,0:52:13.59,Default,,0,0,0,,dread being common. What is that dread\Nof being common? Being looked over, not
Dialogue: 0,0:52:13.59,0:52:17.35,Default,,0,0,0,,being special.\NIf you let go of that one, you let go of
Dialogue: 0,0:52:17.35,0:52:24.07,Default,,0,0,0,,the attraction of a lot of positions.\NIt's better to be anonymous.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:24.07,0:52:31.59,Default,,0,0,0,,You live a lot longer if nobody knows\Nwho the hell you are.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:31.59,0:52:40.96,Default,,0,0,0,,You don't have to go around the the\Ntrack below zero.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:40.96,0:52:46.16,Default,,0,0,0,,All right? So it wants to be superior\Nand for some reason it just hates being
Dialogue: 0,0:52:46.16,0:52:51.59,Default,,0,0,0,,common. It wants to speak up instead of\Nshutting up.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:51.59,0:52:57.44,Default,,0,0,0,,99% of speech is really non-intigorous.\NIf you calibrate the level of free
Dialogue: 0,0:52:57.44,0:53:03.76,Default,,0,0,0,,speech as a concept,\Nit's like I don't know 340 or something.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:03.76,0:53:09.68,Default,,0,0,0,,If you calibrate it as it is practiced\Nin the United States right now, it's
Dialogue: 0,0:53:09.68,0:53:14.40,Default,,0,0,0,,about 187.\NNow, people talk about free speech is
Dialogue: 0,0:53:14.40,0:53:18.64,Default,,0,0,0,,that as though that is the highest prize\Nof civilization.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:18.64,0:53:22.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Think about it. Is that the highest\Nprize of civilization?
Dialogue: 0,0:53:22.80,0:53:28.00,Default,,0,0,0,,That any idiot can go on TV and just\Nrattle away?
Dialogue: 0,0:53:28.00,0:53:38.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Is that the highest good of mankind?\NShould we die for that?
Dialogue: 0,0:53:38.07,0:53:44.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Speaking up is usually about 99% ego and\N1% fact. 1% fact.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:44.88,0:53:51.28,Default,,0,0,0,,1% fact. The rest is people like to hear\Nthe hear themselves talk. Huh?
Dialogue: 0,0:53:51.28,0:53:58.72,Default,,0,0,0,,So being silent then is anathema to the\Nego. The ego is stubborn. Hates to give
Dialogue: 0,0:53:58.72,0:54:05.11,Default,,0,0,0,,in. wants to be famous, hates the idea\Nof being anonymous.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:05.11,0:54:10.64,Default,,0,0,0,,All right. The attra attraction to\Nchange here is resisting and to defend
Dialogue: 0,0:54:10.64,0:54:16.72,Default,,0,0,0,,defend your position rather than to give\Nin because to give in is giving up being
Dialogue: 0,0:54:16.72,0:54:21.11,Default,,0,0,0,,right.\NAnd it views success as getting what it
Dialogue: 0,0:54:21.11,0:54:27.44,Default,,0,0,0,,wants. So whatever the ego decides it\Nwants, that is success. Huh? And it
Dialogue: 0,0:54:27.44,0:54:31.68,Default,,0,0,0,,believes that that is happiness. more\Nmoney, more sex,
Dialogue: 0,0:54:31.68,0:54:37.92,Default,,0,0,0,,more whatever.\NThe attraction to the ego is that of
Dialogue: 0,0:54:37.92,0:54:42.96,Default,,0,0,0,,specialness. It has an aversion to\Ncommonness. It wants more and is afraid
Dialogue: 0,0:54:42.96,0:54:47.04,Default,,0,0,0,,of having less.\NI don't know. Didn't the ego ever have
Dialogue: 0,0:54:47.04,0:54:51.44,Default,,0,0,0,,less? I mean, it's great\Nless. There's lots of things. Just think
Dialogue: 0,0:54:51.44,0:54:55.76,Default,,0,0,0,,how wonderful it would be if you had\Nless of them. All right. To own a thing
Dialogue: 0,0:54:55.76,0:55:02.48,Default,,0,0,0,,then is its claim of specialness. And in\Nreality, it doesn't want to look at the
Dialogue: 0,0:55:02.48,0:55:09.04,Default,,0,0,0,,fact. It only has temporary stewardship.\NNo matter what you own, it's only a
Dialogue: 0,0:55:09.04,0:55:13.92,Default,,0,0,0,,temporary stewardship.\NTemporary stewardship. You can't
Dialogue: 0,0:55:13.92,0:55:20.24,Default,,0,0,0,,actually own anything. To own it, you\Nwould have to be it.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:20.24,0:55:30.72,Default,,0,0,0,,That's a nicity of comprehension.\NTo own this, I would have to be it.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:30.72,0:55:39.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Otherwise, all I have is a claim. Claim.\NThe attraction is to attraction itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:39.68,0:55:43.92,Default,,0,0,0,,The aversion is to plainness and\Nordinary words.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:43.92,0:55:49.59,Default,,0,0,0,,The ego with the wind will like to warp\Nfacts and it really dislikes the truth.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:49.59,0:55:53.83,Default,,0,0,0,,It dislikes the truth.\NWe'll see what the reaction is to the
Dialogue: 0,0:55:53.83,0:56:01.28,Default,,0,0,0,,book going all culting truth versus\Nfalsehood.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:01.28,0:56:06.16,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll see how popular the truth is.\NRight.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:06.16,0:56:11.83,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Couple weeks through soon. Anyway, all\Nright.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:11.83,0:56:17.76,Default,,0,0,0,,It wants to warp facts and every night\Nyou can hear that on television. Uh the
Dialogue: 0,0:56:17.76,0:56:20.72,Default,,0,0,0,,interviewer asks the person the\Nquestion, he doesn't answer the
Dialogue: 0,0:56:20.72,0:56:26.64,Default,,0,0,0,,question. He sidesteps it and gives you\Nsome alternate subject.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:26.64,0:56:33.35,Default,,0,0,0,,That's you can tell he's a politician\Nright the way.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:33.35,0:56:38.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The ego wants to condemn rather than\Nforgive.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:38.00,0:56:43.83,Default,,0,0,0,,So how can we forgive such violations of\Nthe truth? It's because we see that the
Dialogue: 0,0:56:43.83,0:56:49.20,Default,,0,0,0,,ego unabated\Nis addicted and has to win. It doesn't
Dialogue: 0,0:56:49.20,0:56:55.83,Default,,0,0,0,,have any choice. It chooses only the\Ngood and the good is to win. Therefore,
Dialogue: 0,0:56:55.83,0:57:01.92,Default,,0,0,0,,we forgive the politician for lying\Nthrough his teeth and
Dialogue: 0,0:57:01.92,0:57:06.79,Default,,0,0,0,,with his hand on a Bible lying through\Nhis teeth. And you say, "God,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:06.79,0:57:10.48,Default,,0,0,0,,the karma of that, you know, when you\Nget on the other side,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:10.48,0:57:15.68,Default,,0,0,0,,when you get on the other side, but\Nwe're spiritually aware." All right. So,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:15.68,0:57:19.35,Default,,0,0,0,,we know that there are karmic\Nconsequences.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:19.35,0:57:27.35,Default,,0,0,0,,To warp the facts then is what politics\Nis all about. The ego wants to condemn
Dialogue: 0,0:57:27.35,0:57:34.88,Default,,0,0,0,,rather than forgive. It doesn't want\Nexcuse. And the pop the populace
Dialogue: 0,0:57:34.88,0:57:42.24,Default,,0,0,0,,has like a dread of what if a guilty guy\Ngoes free?
Dialogue: 0,0:57:42.24,0:57:50.24,Default,,0,0,0,,You hear almost a panic, emotional panic\Nthat a guilty guy went free. So
Dialogue: 0,0:57:50.24,0:57:55.68,Default,,0,0,0,,So he went free. Yeah, he went free in\Nthe perceptual world, but he did not
Dialogue: 0,0:57:55.68,0:58:03.11,Default,,0,0,0,,escape the karma. All right. Because\NAll right. So we can forgive. Realize
Dialogue: 0,0:58:03.11,0:58:08.07,Default,,0,0,0,,that people are driven by choosing what\Nthey see as the good. And if the good is
Dialogue: 0,0:58:08.07,0:58:13.35,Default,,0,0,0,,to win, they will sell their soul. They\Nwill sell their soul.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:13.35,0:58:20.16,Default,,0,0,0,,You know the opera Dr. Fostus, you know,\NFostus sells out his integrity of his
Dialogue: 0,0:58:20.16,0:58:25.83,Default,,0,0,0,,soul for temporary gain.\NAnd the end of the opera
Dialogue: 0,0:58:25.83,0:58:32.64,Default,,0,0,0,,is payoff time.\NAnd the doors to hell open. And now now
Dialogue: 0,0:58:32.64,0:58:37.83,Default,,0,0,0,,it's time to pay. Now now it's time to\Npay. Yeah. Very interesting. Karmically
Dialogue: 0,0:58:37.83,0:58:42.72,Default,,0,0,0,,correct. And if you calibrate it is\Ntrue. All right. It wants to hold on to
Dialogue: 0,0:58:42.72,0:58:48.72,Default,,0,0,0,,things rather than let go.\NIt wants to dominate rather than
Dialogue: 0,0:58:48.72,0:58:53.11,Default,,0,0,0,,succumb.\NIt's interested in the linear content
Dialogue: 0,0:58:53.11,0:58:59.04,Default,,0,0,0,,and not the field. Therefore, to win an\Nargument, you'll notice politically
Dialogue: 0,0:58:59.04,0:59:06.96,Default,,0,0,0,,people always ignore the context. They\Nalways ignore the context
Dialogue: 0,0:59:06.96,0:59:18.88,Default,,0,0,0,,because if they included context, what\Nthey're saying would be idiotic. Huh?
Dialogue: 0,0:59:18.88,0:59:22.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah.\NI won't go into current examples, but
Dialogue: 0,0:59:22.31,0:59:28.31,Default,,0,0,0,,they're pretty glaring.\NIt wants abundance and does dislikes for
Dialogue: 0,0:59:28.31,0:59:34.79,Default,,0,0,0,,reality. It wants to be the martyr. If\Nyou can't win, then you can still juice
Dialogue: 0,0:59:34.79,0:59:41.83,Default,,0,0,0,,it by being the martyr and the loser.\NAnd best of all, and very the top of the
Dialogue: 0,0:59:41.83,0:59:46.88,Default,,0,0,0,,popularity list is victim.\NYou get to be victim instead of being
Dialogue: 0,0:59:46.88,0:59:52.55,Default,,0,0,0,,responsible.\NYou know who's to blame? It's funny.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:52.55,0:59:58.07,Default,,0,0,0,,watch listening to television, you hear\Nsome catastrophic event, the first thing
Dialogue: 0,0:59:58.07,1:00:05.92,Default,,0,0,0,,the announcer says, "Who's to blame?"\NThe Brooklyn Bridge fell down. Who's to
Dialogue: 0,1:00:05.92,1:00:10.64,Default,,0,0,0,,blame?\NI mean, who cares who's to blame? But
Dialogue: 0,1:00:10.64,1:00:16.16,Default,,0,0,0,,the vindictiveness of the ego, it\Ninstantly looks for who are we going to
Dialogue: 0,1:00:16.16,1:00:23.52,Default,,0,0,0,,blame? And then we're going to hate them\Nand take revenge on them and beat up.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:23.52,1:00:29.35,Default,,0,0,0,,That's the ego's game. It loves to blame\Nsomebody cuz now you can guiltlessly
Dialogue: 0,1:00:29.35,1:00:34.07,Default,,0,0,0,,hate them and beat up on them and seek\Nrevenge.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:34.07,1:00:42.72,Default,,0,0,0,,You can electrocute them. That's a cool\Nway to go.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:42.72,1:00:49.20,Default,,0,0,0,,never been demonstrated that capital\Npunishment has prevented crime at all.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:49.20,1:00:53.28,Default,,0,0,0,,At one time there were 300 different\Ncrimes that all call for capital
Dialogue: 0,1:00:53.28,1:00:57.11,Default,,0,0,0,,punishment.\NDid the incident in those crimes
Dialogue: 0,1:00:57.11,1:01:04.07,Default,,0,0,0,,diminish or they did not?\N300 crimes were capital. You look at
Dialogue: 0,1:01:04.07,1:01:08.72,Default,,0,0,0,,feudal Europe. You look at the history\Nof Europe. uh there were monarchs in
Dialogue: 0,1:01:08.72,1:01:12.16,Default,,0,0,0,,which there were hundreds of things for\Nwhich you get home etc. and people went
Dialogue: 0,1:01:12.16,1:01:16.88,Default,,0,0,0,,right on doing it anyway.\NRight now we have three times an outlaw.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:16.88,1:01:21.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Right?\NTwice he's been in prison now. He goes
Dialogue: 0,1:01:21.52,1:01:29.11,Default,,0,0,0,,back. The apologists say you can't put a\Nman in prison for stealing a pizza.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:29.11,1:01:36.00,Default,,0,0,0,,He had one down, two down, and he cannot\Nstop stealing a pizza.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:36.00,1:01:44.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Aha.\NThat shows a mental defect, does it not?
Dialogue: 0,1:01:44.64,1:01:49.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Faced with horrible torture beyond\Nbelief,
Dialogue: 0,1:01:49.20,1:01:54.07,Default,,0,0,0,,traitorism\Nflourish in the feudal in in the
Dialogue: 0,1:01:54.07,1:01:58.48,Default,,0,0,0,,monarchies of Europe. Knowing that\Nyou're going to be slowly torn to death
Dialogue: 0,1:01:58.48,1:02:07.52,Default,,0,0,0,,and boiled in oil and gruesome deaths,\Npeople did it anyway.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:07.52,1:02:12.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Who the hell? What would you Who cares\Nwho's president?
Dialogue: 0,1:02:12.07,1:02:15.35,Default,,0,0,0,,To get your guy in means you're going to\Nhave your tongue torn out, your eyes
Dialogue: 0,1:02:15.35,1:02:21.11,Default,,0,0,0,,poked in, your ears ripped off, slowly\Ngutted, and racked on the rack.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:21.11,1:02:27.20,Default,,0,0,0,,People do that all the time.\NHuh? All the time. Thousands go to the
Dialogue: 0,1:02:27.20,1:02:33.44,Default,,0,0,0,,guillotine. Go to the Why? Because they\Nwant to be important and be right and in
Dialogue: 0,1:02:33.44,1:02:38.24,Default,,0,0,0,,their eyes save the world.\NAll right. Conflict is what the ego
Dialogue: 0,1:02:38.24,1:02:42.96,Default,,0,0,0,,likes. It just dislikes peace.\NYou can see the Middle East, they've had
Dialogue: 0,1:02:42.96,1:02:47.11,Default,,0,0,0,,an aversion to peace for, you know,\Nthousands of years. And they go into
Dialogue: 0,1:02:47.11,1:02:51.92,Default,,0,0,0,,peace frights periodically, but they\Nthey quickly manage to have a riot and
Dialogue: 0,1:02:51.92,1:02:56.79,Default,,0,0,0,,get rid of it. So\Nyeah, peace would be the end of the
Dialogue: 0,1:02:56.79,1:03:02.16,Default,,0,0,0,,reason for their existence. Raan and\NTendre of
Dialogue: 0,1:03:02.16,1:03:07.28,Default,,0,0,0,,the fellow that just died there. He\Nlived off hate and conflict and peace
Dialogue: 0,1:03:07.28,1:03:13.59,Default,,0,0,0,,was the last thing he wanted.\NBlame, conflict, the past. The ego loves
Dialogue: 0,1:03:13.59,1:03:20.40,Default,,0,0,0,,to cling to the past and it it avoids\Nthe present. It actually clings to fear
Dialogue: 0,1:03:20.40,1:03:25.92,Default,,0,0,0,,based on the idea that it is because of\Nfear that you survive. It doesn't see
Dialogue: 0,1:03:25.92,1:03:33.35,Default,,0,0,0,,that merely anticipation and planning is\Nsufficient. But it hangs on to fear.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:33.35,1:03:39.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Planning and caution is all that's\Nnecessary to cross the street safely.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:39.11,1:03:43.52,Default,,0,0,0,,You don't have to stand on the curb\Nshaking with fear. You anticipate the
Dialogue: 0,1:03:43.52,1:03:48.79,Default,,0,0,0,,oncoming. You're anticipating. So you\Nact from caution rather than fear.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:48.79,1:03:52.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Caution. Huh? That's something the ego\Nnever thinks about. It thinks it's
Dialogue: 0,1:03:52.88,1:03:56.79,Default,,0,0,0,,either, you know, it's only got this or\Nthat.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:56.79,1:04:00.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Ego looks to excuse itself for\Nresponsibility
Dialogue: 0,1:04:00.24,1:04:05.52,Default,,0,0,0,,and it hates being accountable.\NTherefore, it likes to deny things
Dialogue: 0,1:04:05.52,1:04:12.24,Default,,0,0,0,,rather than admit and it's impatient and\Nit hates to wait. Yeah. So, those are
Dialogue: 0,1:04:12.24,1:04:16.55,Default,,0,0,0,,the characteristics generally. Is that\Nthe last one on the tractions and
Dialogue: 0,1:04:16.55,1:04:18.64,Default,,0,0,0,,aversions?\N>> Yes.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:18.64,1:04:19.83,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Yes.\N>> Huh?
Dialogue: 0,1:04:19.83,1:04:22.40,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Yes. Yes.\N>> Is that the one we just did?
Dialogue: 0,1:04:22.40,1:04:27.92,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Except we will do a specific one.\N>> Did we just do do this or not?
Dialogue: 0,1:04:27.92,1:04:31.11,Default,,0,0,0,,>> We did it.\N>> We did it.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:31.11,1:04:37.68,Default,,0,0,0,,>> I'll change it.\N>> I don't remember doing it.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:37.68,1:04:41.76,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Everybody who thinks we just did it,\Nraise your hand.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:41.76,1:04:50.55,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Okay, you win.\NI would have sworn we haven't done it
Dialogue: 0,1:04:50.55,1:04:56.31,Default,,0,0,0,,yet. Okay,\Nwhich was the next one, Betty?
Dialogue: 0,1:04:56.31,1:05:00.16,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Uh,\Nhey,
Dialogue: 0,1:05:00.16,1:05:08.48,Default,,0,0,0,,>> what?\N>> Oh, we're going to look at uh No, we
Dialogue: 0,1:05:08.48,1:05:13.52,Default,,0,0,0,,want to look at um\N>> it was 44.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:13.52,1:05:22.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, it's a news slide.\NUh 45. We want
Dialogue: 0,1:05:22.96,1:05:27.83,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Yeah, 45. We want to look at shame. We\Nhave two slides on shame.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:27.83,1:05:34.88,Default,,0,0,0,,I was too ashamed to show up. Okay.\NShame is ashamed of itself. I'm ashamed
Dialogue: 0,1:05:34.88,1:05:43.11,Default,,0,0,0,,to be shamed.\N>> You can't get to 45.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:43.11,1:05:48.88,Default,,0,0,0,,What?\N>> Oh, there's no rush.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:48.88,1:05:55.83,Default,,0,0,0,,>> There's no rush.\NThe ego's always in a hurry.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:55.83,1:06:00.96,Default,,0,0,0,,We're in no hurry, right?\NHow can you get a chance to just sit and
Dialogue: 0,1:06:00.96,1:06:13.03,Default,,0,0,0,,do nothing? I mean, it's great.\NWe got to hurry up because we got Nico
Dialogue: 0,1:06:13.03,1:06:17.28,Default,,0,0,0,,about 10 after 3.\N>> Yes, about 10 after. So, we have about
Dialogue: 0,1:06:17.28,1:06:21.44,Default,,0,0,0,,15 minutes.\N>> Well, shame seems to have taken a
Dialogue: 0,1:06:21.44,1:06:25.76,Default,,0,0,0,,holiday.\N>> I thought we'd start at the bottom.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:25.76,1:06:32.96,Default,,0,0,0,,shame because shame often o shows up as\Ndisgrace, depression, hopelessness,
Dialogue: 0,1:06:32.96,1:06:40.07,Default,,0,0,0,,apathy sometimes takes clinical forms\Nnot infrequently ends up as suicide
Dialogue: 0,1:06:40.07,1:06:46.31,Default,,0,0,0,,or the failure to take the necessary\Nsteps to survive.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:46.31,1:06:55.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Shame is banishment.\NIn primitive society, your life depended
Dialogue: 0,1:06:55.11,1:07:02.48,Default,,0,0,0,,on the integrity of the tribe,\Nthe local tribe. And
Dialogue: 0,1:07:02.48,1:07:08.64,Default,,0,0,0,,shame, you were banished. When you were\Nbanished from the tribe, you died.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:08.64,1:07:14.79,Default,,0,0,0,,You had no means of survival. The wild\Nanimals got you. You died of starvation.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:14.79,1:07:22.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Uh so shame was equivalent to death.\NAnd shame is at calibration 20 is very
Dialogue: 0,1:07:22.79,1:07:27.59,Default,,0,0,0,,close to death.\NPeople shrink with shame. They
Dialogue: 0,1:07:27.59,1:07:41.11,Default,,0,0,0,,disappear. They try to become invisible.\NSelf-hatred, the giving up of all hope.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:41.11,1:07:46.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Clinically, it requires treatment. Why?\NBecause the person in shame is lacking
Dialogue: 0,1:07:46.64,1:07:52.64,Default,,0,0,0,,energy and doesn't even have the energy\Nto avail themsself of available energy.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:52.64,1:07:58.07,Default,,0,0,0,,It can't even take advantage of what is\Navailable.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:58.07,1:08:05.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Therefore, it is the lowest level. Huh?\NDisgrace, banishment, shame, despair,
Dialogue: 0,1:08:05.20,1:08:13.20,Default,,0,0,0,,and hopelessness are the bottom of the\Nbox.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:13.20,1:08:21.35,Default,,0,0,0,,not infrequently leads to death.\N>> Clinically, uh it means if you see them
Dialogue: 0,1:08:21.35,1:08:26.56,Default,,0,0,0,,clinically, yeah, uh it's a\Npharmacologic problem. It also has
Dialogue: 0,1:08:26.56,1:08:32.71,Default,,0,0,0,,correlated correlations in brain\Num chemistry, neurochemistry.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:32.71,1:08:37.04,Default,,0,0,0,,The depletion of necessary\Nneurochemicals
Dialogue: 0,1:08:37.04,1:08:44.40,Default,,0,0,0,,allows one to drop to the depths.\NThe alternative actually is death
Dialogue: 0,1:08:44.40,1:08:52.56,Default,,0,0,0,,itself. And unless someone takes action\Non the person's behalf, they will die.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:52.56,1:09:06.48,Default,,0,0,0,,This is a consequence of many things.\NDenial of God is one thing.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:06.48,1:09:12.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Karmic consequence is another\Nabandonment.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:12.88,1:09:19.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Karmic consequence can be quite severe.\NIt is also paradoxically the degree to
Dialogue: 0,1:09:19.19,1:09:23.35,Default,,0,0,0,,which some people have to hit bottom for\Nthe ego to give up.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:23.35,1:09:29.19,Default,,0,0,0,,It's only when\Nyou're clinging to life by one or two
Dialogue: 0,1:09:29.19,1:09:35.35,Default,,0,0,0,,fingers that you're willing to let go.\NThe depths of hell,
Dialogue: 0,1:09:35.35,1:09:40.96,Default,,0,0,0,,hopelessness and despair\Nbeyond description,
Dialogue: 0,1:09:40.96,1:09:50.48,Default,,0,0,0,,and the hopelessness and the despair and\Nthe agony is eternal.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:50.48,1:09:56.40,Default,,0,0,0,,At that level, you get what that means.\NForever
Dialogue: 0,1:09:56.40,1:10:02.15,Default,,0,0,0,,you are condemned to the dark, to the\Nblackness, to hopelessness
Dialogue: 0,1:10:02.15,1:10:09.60,Default,,0,0,0,,without the possibility of any\Nintervention from anywhere.
Dialogue: 0,1:10:09.60,1:10:14.15,Default,,0,0,0,,And time stops.\NAnd just like the top levels of
Dialogue: 0,1:10:14.15,1:10:19.04,Default,,0,0,0,,consciousness are beyond time, you\Nexperience eternity. Anybody who's had a
Dialogue: 0,1:10:19.04,1:10:23.84,Default,,0,0,0,,near-death experience knows what that\Nis. It's outside of time. At the bottom
Dialogue: 0,1:10:23.84,1:10:33.04,Default,,0,0,0,,of the pits is the same timelessness.\NThe soul is lost and abandoned
Dialogue: 0,1:10:33.04,1:10:39.52,Default,,0,0,0,,forever.\NAs you descend to through hell,
Dialogue: 0,1:10:39.52,1:10:45.36,Default,,0,0,0,,the top level is agony,\Nsuffering, torture,
Dialogue: 0,1:10:45.36,1:10:53.12,Default,,0,0,0,,child's play, jacks for openers.\NWhat the real considers hell is
Dialogue: 0,1:10:53.12,1:11:00.15,Default,,0,0,0,,just the opening chapter.\NThen it gets more severe and the agony
Dialogue: 0,1:11:00.15,1:11:04.56,Default,,0,0,0,,is beyond description. And then time\Nstops.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:04.56,1:11:09.67,Default,,0,0,0,,As I've mentioned before, as you descend\Ninto the pits of hell,
Dialogue: 0,1:11:09.67,1:11:13.76,Default,,0,0,0,,you come to a knowingness which Dante\Nknew.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:13.76,1:11:18.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Abandon all hope, ye who enter here.\NThere it was, just as plain as day, is
Dialogue: 0,1:11:18.64,1:11:24.48,Default,,0,0,0,,all written on a bulletin board. How\NDante knew it, I don't know.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:24.48,1:11:31.76,Default,,0,0,0,,And from there, it gets bad.\NAnd then you experience like damnation,
Dialogue: 0,1:11:31.76,1:11:37.76,Default,,0,0,0,,hopelessness for eternity.\NOut of the eternity of hopelessness,
Dialogue: 0,1:11:37.76,1:11:44.80,Default,,0,0,0,,then out of nowhere arose a voice that\Nsaid, "And if there is a God, I ask him
Dialogue: 0,1:11:44.80,1:11:50.56,Default,,0,0,0,,for help."\NAnd then all of it blacked out.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:50.56,1:11:56.80,Default,,0,0,0,,And the next thing was\Nstanding in the full radiance of
Dialogue: 0,1:11:56.80,1:12:10.40,Default,,0,0,0,,divinity as the allness of creation and\Nlife itself.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:10.40,1:12:16.88,Default,,0,0,0,,If that's what it takes, then that's\Nwhat it takes.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:16.88,1:12:22.48,Default,,0,0,0,,I wouldn't recommend it, but\Nif that's what it takes, that's what it
Dialogue: 0,1:12:22.48,1:12:28.32,Default,,0,0,0,,takes. Therefore, when I see people do\Nserious violations, serious spiritual
Dialogue: 0,1:12:28.32,1:12:32.56,Default,,0,0,0,,violations that I know have very bad\Nkarmic consequences, it makes me shudder
Dialogue: 0,1:12:32.56,1:12:38.88,Default,,0,0,0,,because I know what's coming.\NRemember that kid who was executed?
Dialogue: 0,1:12:38.88,1:12:42.64,Default,,0,0,0,,What did he do? Blow up a building or\Nsomething? And he said, "Well, I know
Dialogue: 0,1:12:42.64,1:12:47.12,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm going to hell, but there'll be good\Ncompany there." When he gets there,
Dialogue: 0,1:12:47.12,1:12:53.28,Default,,0,0,0,,you'll find it isn't that way at all.\NIt's agony. So if that's what it takes.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:53.28,1:12:59.12,Default,,0,0,0,,So some people\Nuh at the bottom of the have to go all
Dialogue: 0,1:12:59.12,1:13:04.23,Default,,0,0,0,,the way to the bottom\Nin order to find God.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:04.23,1:13:10.88,Default,,0,0,0,,The ego's struggle for survival at least\Nin this case was ferocious.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:10.88,1:13:16.80,Default,,0,0,0,,It was ferocious. It was\Nit would not let go.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:16.80,1:13:21.52,Default,,0,0,0,,That's what it took to make the ego let\Ngo. Huh? Usually just swimming it on the
Dialogue: 0,1:13:21.52,1:13:29.92,Default,,0,0,0,,fingers will do it, but no.\NOh god, I must have had the ego of a sea
Dialogue: 0,1:13:29.92,1:13:34.40,Default,,0,0,0,,urchin or something out of the sea, you\Nknow.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:34.40,1:13:40.40,Default,,0,0,0,,All right. So the attractions a shame is\Nheld into place besides karmic factors
Dialogue: 0,1:13:40.40,1:13:46.00,Default,,0,0,0,,which in this case was the karma of\Nhaving denied the reality of God in
Dialogue: 0,1:13:46.00,1:13:53.36,Default,,0,0,0,,other lifetimes having defied and\Nperhaps even worse than that. Uh so that
Dialogue: 0,1:13:53.36,1:13:58.96,Default,,0,0,0,,was the undoing of that. All right.\NOne thing attractive about shame is you
Dialogue: 0,1:13:58.96,1:14:04.64,Default,,0,0,0,,get to punish yourself.\NTherefore, to forgive yourself would be
Dialogue: 0,1:14:04.64,1:14:11.04,Default,,0,0,0,,just what you won't do.\NThe attraction is to stay depressed. The
Dialogue: 0,1:14:11.04,1:14:16.64,Default,,0,0,0,,aversion is to choose life. Sometimes it\Ntakes electric shock treatments to take
Dialogue: 0,1:14:16.64,1:14:22.23,Default,,0,0,0,,the person out of that.\NThe attraction is judgmental and being
Dialogue: 0,1:14:22.23,1:14:28.80,Default,,0,0,0,,judgmental against yourself instead of\Nsurrendering to God's mercy.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:28.80,1:14:36.96,Default,,0,0,0,,The attraction here is to be negative\Nrather than let go of your position
Dialogue: 0,1:14:36.96,1:14:41.84,Default,,0,0,0,,shame. You sh you you shrink. You hide\Nand you don't want the light on you to
Dialogue: 0,1:14:41.84,1:14:47.19,Default,,0,0,0,,be visible. You see yourself as\Nworthless and your aversion is to affirm
Dialogue: 0,1:14:47.19,1:14:52.15,Default,,0,0,0,,the gift of life itself.\NHere your view of self is unforgiving
Dialogue: 0,1:14:52.15,1:14:57.44,Default,,0,0,0,,and rigid and you don't want to correct\Nit and be flexible.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:57.44,1:15:02.08,Default,,0,0,0,,So if somebody's stuck in this and I\Ntell them what Socrates teaching is,
Dialogue: 0,1:15:02.08,1:15:06.32,Default,,0,0,0,,they'll say, "Well, that's okay." But\Nthey won't apply it. Huh? So they cling
Dialogue: 0,1:15:06.32,1:15:13.52,Default,,0,0,0,,to it. A rigid self view.\NRather condemn than forgive.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:13.52,1:15:22.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It seeks mortification\Nrather than to choose self-worth.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:22.00,1:15:26.32,Default,,0,0,0,,The physicality was a gift of being a\Nhuman.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:26.32,1:15:30.56,Default,,0,0,0,,What would be the point of mortifying\Nit? But the downside, the Gothic side of
Dialogue: 0,1:15:30.56,1:15:36.96,Default,,0,0,0,,religion at one time was very into\Nmortification of the body. Sackcloth and
Dialogue: 0,1:15:36.96,1:15:42.80,Default,,0,0,0,,ashes, hair shirts. Huh.\NThe attraction here is to denigrate
Dialogue: 0,1:15:42.80,1:15:47.76,Default,,0,0,0,,value and worth rather than to honor\Nyourself.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:47.76,1:15:55.19,Default,,0,0,0,,All spiritually aligned people owe it as\Nan obligation to honor oneself to honor
Dialogue: 0,1:15:55.19,1:15:59.12,Default,,0,0,0,,one's dedication.\NYou owe it to yourself out of honor.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:59.12,1:16:04.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah. To honor. Yeah. Here I'd rather\Ndenigrate
Dialogue: 0,1:16:04.64,1:16:08.23,Default,,0,0,0,,because then it can indulge in\Nself-hatred.
Dialogue: 0,1:16:08.23,1:16:15.28,Default,,0,0,0,,The ego loves hatred.\NIt loves negativity. The ego survives on
Dialogue: 0,1:16:15.28,1:16:21.19,Default,,0,0,0,,the juice it gets out of its positions.\NSee the ego has no condundalini
Dialogue: 0,1:16:21.19,1:16:27.84,Default,,0,0,0,,spiritual energy from which to thrive\Nonly animal energy. So it has to extract
Dialogue: 0,1:16:27.84,1:16:34.56,Default,,0,0,0,,juice every ego position in order to\Nsurvive.
Dialogue: 0,1:16:34.56,1:16:38.71,Default,,0,0,0,,The condundolini energy is some\Ncompletely different. All you have to do
Dialogue: 0,1:16:38.71,1:16:43.67,Default,,0,0,0,,is say yes to it and it influences the\Nfield and things come about
Dialogue: 0,1:16:43.67,1:16:48.80,Default,,0,0,0,,effortlessly.\NThe downside is it loves severity rather
Dialogue: 0,1:16:48.80,1:16:54.71,Default,,0,0,0,,than being benign.\NYou see the severity selfagulation
Dialogue: 0,1:16:54.71,1:17:00.23,Default,,0,0,0,,suicide\Nand the downside of current war it's in
Dialogue: 0,1:17:00.23,1:17:04.08,Default,,0,0,0,,balanced and it doesn't want to see both\Nsides. Doesn't want to hear the other
Dialogue: 0,1:17:04.08,1:17:10.48,Default,,0,0,0,,side of the story. wants to keep\Nmaintain a distortion. Next slide.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:10.48,1:17:20.08,Default,,0,0,0,,>> That's it for you.\N>> That's the next slide.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:20.08,1:17:24.88,Default,,0,0,0,,>> So, keep going.\N>> Is this a different slide?
Dialogue: 0,1:17:24.88,1:17:29.12,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Oh, okay.\NIt's a different slide. All right. Here
Dialogue: 0,1:17:29.12,1:17:33.28,Default,,0,0,0,,you like to blame yourself\Nrather than blame the ignorance of the
Dialogue: 0,1:17:33.28,1:17:39.92,Default,,0,0,0,,ego. So that you refute Socrates wisdom.\NSocrates wisdom is at 570. And if you're
Dialogue: 0,1:17:39.92,1:17:45.92,Default,,0,0,0,,more higher than 570, it's okay to\Nrefute Socrates.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:45.92,1:17:52.56,Default,,0,0,0,,I hate somebody at 170 telling me\NSocrates don't know what from us.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:52.56,1:17:57.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah.\NAll right. So blame the self instead of
Dialogue: 0,1:17:57.92,1:18:03.12,Default,,0,0,0,,seeing that that we all make the best it\Nseemed like the best decision at the
Dialogue: 0,1:18:03.12,1:18:08.00,Default,,0,0,0,,time. So to blame yourself you have to\Nto stop blaming yourself you have to see
Dialogue: 0,1:18:08.00,1:18:12.88,Default,,0,0,0,,that the context was different and the\Nperson you are now is not the same as
Dialogue: 0,1:18:12.88,1:18:19.36,Default,,0,0,0,,the person you were then. See who you\Nare now is not what you were. So what
Dialogue: 0,1:18:19.36,1:18:26.96,Default,,0,0,0,,you were was uh more limited. Huh? And\Nokay so it wants to maintain its partial
Dialogue: 0,1:18:26.96,1:18:33.19,Default,,0,0,0,,selective view to justify rather than a\Nbalanced. It wants to see the self as
Dialogue: 0,1:18:33.19,1:18:38.71,Default,,0,0,0,,loser rather than see himself as\Ncorrected.
Dialogue: 0,1:18:38.71,1:18:44.96,Default,,0,0,0,,It wants to see life as the end of the\Nroad instead of the opening to the new.
Dialogue: 0,1:18:44.96,1:18:49.67,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll tell you in the pits of hell I had\Nno idea that was the road to the opening
Dialogue: 0,1:18:49.67,1:18:58.40,Default,,0,0,0,,of the new.\Nthe opening of the new wife. Here you're
Dialogue: 0,1:18:58.40,1:19:04.96,Default,,0,0,0,,absolute absolutely unlovable\Nand you deny your worth as a child of
Dialogue: 0,1:19:04.96,1:19:12.00,Default,,0,0,0,,God. All that exists arises out of one\Nsource. So it's a denial of the truth of
Dialogue: 0,1:19:12.00,1:19:16.88,Default,,0,0,0,,who you are. Here you see error as\Nunforgivable.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:16.88,1:19:40.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Here you see it as a lesson. Well, leion\Nis correct too.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:40.88,1:19:46.08,Default,,0,0,0,,All right. So, so all these ego, this is\Na narcissistic orientation. It's all me.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:46.08,1:19:50.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, me my guilt. Oh, me my error. Oh, me\Nhow unforgivable. You see how me that
Dialogue: 0,1:19:50.56,1:19:57.76,Default,,0,0,0,,is? It's just me all over the place.\NInstead of being concerned for others
Dialogue: 0,1:19:57.76,1:20:02.00,Default,,0,0,0,,here, you're serving your personal self.\NHere you're going to serve life. You can
Dialogue: 0,1:20:02.00,1:20:07.76,Default,,0,0,0,,see this is an enormous self-indulgence\Nto wallow in guilt and shame and penance
Dialogue: 0,1:20:07.76,1:20:13.28,Default,,0,0,0,,and sackloth and ashes and drag yourself\Naround as the poor suffering martyr.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:13.28,1:20:19.19,Default,,0,0,0,,I know people have tragedies, routine\Ntragedies which everybody has to face 30
Dialogue: 0,1:20:19.19,1:20:24.32,Default,,0,0,0,,years ago and they're still juicing\Nthem. Still juicing them,
Dialogue: 0,1:20:24.32,1:20:31.04,Default,,0,0,0,,you know, still juicing them.\NAll right? Because it's selfindulgent.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:31.04,1:20:36.71,Default,,0,0,0,,It sees self as center of life rather\Nthan just a part participant.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:36.71,1:20:42.08,Default,,0,0,0,,It focuses on oneself instead of on\Nothers. So you're constantly dumping
Dialogue: 0,1:20:42.08,1:20:46.56,Default,,0,0,0,,your misery of what happened 30 years\Nago and trying to milk people in the
